  "response": "Based on current scientific understanding from cosmic microwave background radiation studies using the Cosmic Background Explorer (COBE) satellite, the Milky Way is moving at approximately 630 km/s relative to the cosmic microwave background radiation. However, the orientation of the galaxy (whether edge-on or face-on) during this motion is not specifically defined or known from this data.\n\nThe velocity and direction of the galaxy's motion are well-established, but the specific rotational orientation of the galaxy's disk relative to its trajectory is not a parameter that was definitively determined by the COBE survey. The motion is described in terms of the galaxy's overall center of mass movement through space.\n\nThe motion is typically referenced to the cosmic microwave background radiation's rest frame, indicating the galaxy's bulk movement relative to the early universe's radiation background. But this does not specify the precise angular orientation of the galactic disk during this motion.\n\nAstronomers can calculate the galaxy's velocity vector, but the exact rotational orientation would require additional observational and analytical techniques beyond the COBE survey's primary measurements.",
